---

<Layout
  title="Solar profitability and ROI by Moroccan city | Blog Taqinor"
  description="5–7 year payback, production by city and ONEE tariffs: everything you need to know about solar profitability in Morocco."
  ogSlug="residentiel"
>
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(blogPosting)} />
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(breadcrumbLd)} />
  <div class="v2">
    <V2Enhance />
    <Article33Ribbon />

    <Breadcrumb items={[{ label: 'Home', href: L('/') }, { label: 'Blog', href: L('/blog') }, { label: 'Solar profitability by city' }]} />

    <article class="mx-auto max-w-[68ch] px-4 pb-24 pt-12 sm:pb-28">
      <p class="tech-label v2-kicker rule-brass text-brass-300">
        Blog · {dateFmt.format(pubDate)} · by Reda Kasri
      </p>
      <h1 class="display v2-page-title mt-5 text-white">Solar profitability and ROI by Moroccan city</h1>

      <p class="article-meta mt-3 flex items-center gap-2 text-xs text-lune-faint">
        {readingMinutes} min read
      </p>

      <p class="prose-lead mt-5">5–7 year payback, production by city and ONEE tariffs: everything you need to know about solar profitability in Morocco.</p>

      <div class="prose mt-10">
        <p>
          When a client asks me whether "solar is profitable for them", my first question isn't the
          price. It's: which city, and what's your ONEE tariff bracket? These two parameters often
          weigh more than the panel brand. Here's how I reason about it, with the figures I have on
          hand.
        </p>

        <h2>Solar production by city: how many kWh per kWc installed?</h2>
        <p>
          It all starts with <strong>site yield</strong>, i.e. the number of kWh produced per kWc
          installed per year (called PVOUT). It depends on local sunshine, panel tilt, and system
          losses: wiring, inverter, dust on the glass.
        </p>
        <p>
          The table below gives estimated brackets, calculated from PVGIS, Global
          Solar Atlas and Solargis data, with a system loss rate of about 14% and due-south
          orientation, with an estimated optimal tilt for each city.
        </p>
        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr>
                <th>City</th>
                <th>Estimated PVOUT (kWh/kWc/yr)</th>
                <th>Estimated optimal tilt (due south)</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              {pvout.map((p) => (
                <tr>
                  <td>{p.city}</td>
                  <td>{p.value}</td>
                  <td>{p.tilt}</td>
                </tr>
              ))}
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
        <p><em>Sources: PVGIS (European Commission); Global Solar Atlas (World Bank / Solargis); MDPI Resources 2024 13(10):140 (Marrakech, PR 78%). Other cities' brackets are estimates recalibrated on the Marrakech point — not a substitute for a PVGIS simulation at your exact address.</em></p>
        <blockquote><p><strong>Consistency note:</strong> our <a href={L('/ensoleillement-maroc')}>yield-by-city page</a>, drawn directly from our own PVGIS TMY 2005–2020 extraction (14% system losses, PR 86%), gives lower values for these same cities (Marrakech ~1,650, Casablanca ~1,650, Agadir ~1,686 kWh/kWc/yr) — an ~8% gap versus the Marrakech point above. This isn't a contradiction: the MDPI study measures GTI (plane-of-array irradiation) and applies its own performance-ratio assumption (PR 78%), different from our own PVGIS extraction (PR 86%) — two distinct methodologies applied to the same solar resource don't yield the same final PVOUT. For an estimate that exactly reflects our sizing method, see <a href={L('/ensoleillement-maroc')}>yield by city</a> and <a href={L('/methodologie-estimation')}>our estimation methodology</a>.</p></blockquote>
        <p>
          <strong>National benchmark:</strong> Morocco's PVOUT band sits between
          <strong> 1,600 and 1,900 kWh/kWc/yr</strong> (GSA). Installers often use the rule of thumb
          <strong> 1,500–1,800 kWh/kWc/yr depending on region</strong>.
        </p>

        <h2>Why is solar profitable in Morocco? The ONEE tariff mechanism</h2>
        <h3>The tariff grid (verified by the founder, June 2026)</h3>
        <p>Current ONEE/régie residential low-voltage tariffs are as follows (incl. VAT, the <code>REGIE_TARIFF</code> grid — the same one our online estimator uses):</p>
        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr>
                <th>Monthly consumption</th>
                <th>Tariff (DH/kWh)</th>
                <th>Billing mode</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              {tariffs.map((t) => (
                <tr>
                  <td>{t.range}</td>
                  <td>{t.tariff}</td>
                  <td>{t.mode}</td>
                </tr>
              ))}
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
        <p><em>Grid verified by the founder (June 2026), identical to the one our online estimator applies — see <a href={L('/methodologie-estimation')}>our estimation methodology</a> and <a href={L('/ensoleillement-maroc')}>yield by city</a> for the live source. Lydec/Casablanca and Redal/Rabat are currently matched to this same grid (a conservative posture pending a reference bill from each utility); Amendis/Tangier follows the same bracket structure. An older grid (0.90/1.07/1.18/1.45/1.66 DH/kWh, sourced ~2015 via aggregators like kherba.com and calculateur.ma) previously appeared on this article — it is <strong>replaced</strong> by the grid above, more precise and aligned with the estimator.</em></p>
        <blockquote><p><strong>Freshness note:</strong> these tariffs have been stable for several years. Check <a href="https://calculateur.ma">calculateur.ma</a> or with your distributor if you're reading this article after 2026.</p></blockquote>

        <h3>The "selective" mechanism: solar's leverage effect</h3>
        <p>This is the key point many consumers miss:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Below <strong>150 kWh/month</strong>, billing is <strong>progressive</strong>: each bracket is billed at its own rate.</li>
          <li>Above <strong>150 kWh/month</strong>, billing becomes <strong>"selective"</strong>: <strong>the entire month's consumption</strong> is billed at the rate of the bracket reached.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          <strong>Concrete example:</strong> a household consuming 250 kWh in July doesn't pay the
          first 100 kWh at 0.9010 DH then the rest at 1.0732… It pays the <em>entire</em> 250 kWh at
          the 211–310 kWh bracket rate, 1.1676 DH/kWh (a 10 kWh tolerance per bracket softens
          narrow overshoots).
        </p>
        <p>
          What solar removes is precisely this high marginal rate applied to the whole bill. Take a
          household in the 311–510 kWh bracket that pulls 200 kWh a month off the grid thanks to its
          panels: it saves those 200 kWh at the <em>marginal</em> rate of 1.3817 DH, not at the apparent
          average rate of its old bill. That's the whole reason profitability climbs for heavy
          consumers, and it's also what I check first on a bill before pricing anything.
        </p>

        <h2>Return on investment: 5 to 7 years (installer consensus)</h2>
        <p>
          The <strong>standard residential payback</strong> is <strong>5 to 7 years</strong> — a
          figure consistent across all the installer sources consulted (solaropeak.com, ecovolt.ma,
          electrosolarplus.ma, lechantier.ma).
        </p>
        <p><strong>What influences payback:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Your current tariff bracket</strong>: the higher your bracket (≥ 1.3817 DH/kWh), the greater the annual savings and the faster the payback.</li>
          <li><strong>Installation cost</strong>: indicative 2026 bracket of ~10,000 to 14,000 DH/kWc (equipment + install, installer sources — unaudited). See <a href={L('/blog/prix-installation-solaire-maroc-2026')}>our pricing guide</a>.</li>
          <li><strong>Your self-consumption rate</strong>: <a href={L('/loi-82-21')}>Law 82-21</a> organises low-voltage self-generation, but no residential (BT) buy-back tariff is published yet — the ANRE has only published a buy-back tariff for medium/high/very-high voltage (0.18–0.21 DH/kWh), not for homes under 11 kW. Until that BT tariff exists in black and white, we don't price in <strong>any export revenue</strong>: solar's real value is in immediate consumption, not in reselling an unvalued surplus (see <a href={L('/methodologie-estimation')}>our estimation methodology</a>).</li>
          <li><strong>The battery</strong>: adding storage stretches payback by <strong>1 to 3 years</strong> but increases the evening self-consumption rate.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          <strong>Over 30 years</strong>, once the installation is paid off, every kWh produced is
          nearly free. Modern panels lose about 0.4%/year of performance and the old market standard
          (PERC cells) guaranteed them at ~80–85% of initial capacity at 25 years — the N-type panels we install
          go beyond it: a <strong>linear performance warranty over 30 years</strong>, at
          <strong>≥ 87.4% of initial power at 30 years</strong> (i.e. ≥ 89.4% at 25 years).
        </p>

        <h2>Simulate your installation</h2>
        <p>
          The figures above are market brackets. Your real profitability depends on your
          consumption, your city, and your roof's surface and orientation.
          <a href={L('/devis/mon-toit')}>Get a personalised quote</a> for a precise estimate.
        </p>
        <hr />
        <p><em>ONEE/régie tariffs (<code>REGIE_TARIFF</code> grid) verified by the founder, June 2026. Yields by city: PVGIS/Global Solar Atlas/Solargis estimates recalibrated on the Marrakech measurement of 1,779 kWh/kWc/yr (MDPI Resources 2024, PR 78%) — this field study uses a performance-ratio assumption different from Taqinor's own PVGIS TMY extraction (PR 86%, see <a href={L('/ensoleillement-maroc')}>/ensoleillement-maroc</a>), which explains the ~8% gap versus the site's own yield table: the two figures don't contradict each other, they apply different methodologies. Payback 5–7 years: consensus of 2026 Moroccan installer sources.</em></p>
      </div>

      <RelatedLinks
        links={[
          { href: L('/blog'), label: 'All the articles' },
          { href: L('/guides'), label: 'The evergreen guides' },
          { href: L('/financement'), label: 'Financing & returns' },
        ]}
      />
    </article>

    <CtaBand title="These are city averages. Your own payback comes from your own bill." href={L('/devis/mon-toit')} />

    <StickyCta />
  </div>
</Layout>
